In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims February as American Heart Month. He emphasizes the importance of taking steps to reduce the risk of heart disease, which is the leading cause of death in the United States. The President encourages Americans to make healthy lifestyle choices, such as eating balanced meals, maintaining a healthy weight, and being physically active. He also highlights the Million Hearts initiative, which aims to prevent one million heart attacks and strokes over the next five years through coordinated programs and partnerships. The First Lady's Let's Move! initiative focuses on promoting healthy eating habits and physical activity among families and young people to end childhood obesity. The National Institutes of Health conducts research to develop new treatments for cardiovascular disease, and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention work to reduce risk factors and prevent heart disease in communities. The President also mentions The Heart Truth campaign, which raises awareness about heart disease in women, and encourages Americans to participate in National Wear Red Day on February 3 to show support for the campaign. The President concludes by urging all Americans to join him in fighting cardiovascular disease and reaffirming their commitment to better heart health.